docs {
  # atomic-fi-scenarios

  The canonical Bruno collection for the **AtomicFi payments compliance platform**.
  Every regulatory scenario from the use-case catalog at
  [`guides/use-cases.md`](https://github.com/alvera-ai/atomic-fi/blob/main/guides/use-cases.md)
  is exercised here against the live HTTP API, so the same artefact serves three purposes:

  - **Demo tape** — Bruno's recursive runner walks the entire collection in one click,
    producing realistic data and a green status board suitable for a live customer demo.
  - **Regression smoke** — `bru run --env local` from CI catches contract drift between
    the OpenAPI spec, the Phoenix controllers, and the documented scenarios.
  - **Compliance evidence** — each scenario maps to a row in the catalog, so a regulator
    or auditor can request "scenario §2.3.1 (OFAC SDN exact match)" and receive exactly
    one piece of executable evidence with one assertion path.

  ## What's here today

  | Folder | Purpose | Count |
  | --- | --- | --- |
  | `smoke-tests/` | Baseline data-seeding smoke. Auth → BlocklistCache warmup → 2 AccountHolders → 5 Counterparties → 20 Transactions. Idempotent re-runs (counterparty_number is the external SoE id). | 29 requests |

  Future folders mirror the regulatory regimes in `guides/use-cases.md` (`01-cip/`,
  `02-ofac-sanctions/`, `03-edd/`, `04-cta-ubo/`, `05-aml-velocity/`, etc.), one `.bru`
  file per scenario.

  ## Quick start

  1. **Install Bruno** — `brew install --cask bruno` or download from <https://www.usebruno.com>.
  2. **Bring atomic-fi up locally** from the repo root:
     ```
     make run-backing-services   # docker compose: upstream moov/watchman on :8084
     make server                  # Phoenix on :4100
     ```
  3. **Refresh bootstrap creds** so the local env matches what's in the running DB:
     ```
     mix atomic_fi.dump_bootstrap_creds
     ```
  4. **Copy the env template** (one-time):
     ```
     cp environments/local.example.bru environments/local.bru
     ```
     Then edit `local.bru` with the values from `priv/repo/.bootstrap_creds.json`.
  5. **Run the smoke** — either click the Runner button in the Bruno UI, or from CLI:
     ```
     cd bruno/atomic-fi-scenarios
     bru run smoke-tests --env local
     ```

  Expected result: **29/29 requests pass, 66/66 assertions green** in roughly 4 seconds.

  ## Authentication

  All requests after `001-auth.bru` use bearer authentication. `001-auth.bru` exchanges
  `{email, password, tenant_slug}` for a session bearer via `POST /api/sessions`; the
  token, tenant id, and running id arrays (`ahIds`, `cpIds`) are stashed as env vars by
  the post-response script and reused by every downstream request.

  `001-auth.bru` also resets the running id arrays on every invocation, so re-runs start
  from a clean state without manual env clearing.

  ## Design principles

  - **Real Watchman, real BlocklistCache, real DB.** No mocks anywhere — compliance
    scenarios must validate the actual pipeline. The compose-managed
    `moov/watchman:v0.61.1` container is part of the test harness.
  - **One scenario, one `.bru` file.** A regulator can request "scenario 23" and receive
    exactly one piece of executable evidence.
  - **Child entities are nested via `cast_assoc`**, not created via standalone endpoints.
    A counterparty POST carries its LegalEntity inline; the HTTP surface stays smaller
    than the DB schema count.
  - **Idempotency via the external SoE identifier.** Counterparty creation is
    get-or-create on `counterparty_number`; the same POST replayed returns the original
    record unchanged. Updates use PUT.
  - **Per-tenant RLS isolation.** Every assertion runs inside the platform tenant's
    session scope; cross-tenant visibility is explicitly tested via secondary tenants in
    the regulatory folders.

  ## Related

  - [`guides/use-cases.md`](https://github.com/alvera-ai/atomic-fi/blob/main/guides/use-cases.md) — the catalog (source of truth for scenarios)
  - [`integration-tests/`](https://github.com/alvera-ai/atomic-fi/tree/main/integration-tests) — vitest mirror against the same live server
  - [`test/atomic_fi/`](https://github.com/alvera-ai/atomic-fi/tree/main/test/atomic_fi) — ExUnit context + controller tests (in-process, no HTTP)
  - [`CLAUDE.md`](https://github.com/alvera-ai/atomic-fi/blob/main/CLAUDE.md) — Controller / Context Contract, OpenAPI Schema Patterns, Multi-Tenancy Pattern
